 INSTRUCTIONS: \
_______________
\b0 \
 \
To use VideoMax in your Flash project, you must import the VideoMax class into your file, create a new instance, and add it to the display list.\
 	\
Setting VideoMax attributes can be done in two different ways, as seen in the two examples outlined below.\
 \
1) Setting Object Attributes on Creation (RECOMMENDED):\
 		\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural

\f1 \cf0 import com.hd.VideoMax;\
\cf2 var\cf0  vm = \cf2 new\cf0  VideoMax(\{\cf2 width\cf0 :640, \cf2 height\cf0 :480, tint:[0x1c1c1c, 0xffffff], source:\cf3 "sample.flv"\cf0 \});\
\cf2 addChild\cf0 (vm);
\f0 \
		\
		\
2) Setting Individual Attributes After Creation:\
 		\

\f1 \cf2 import\cf0  com.hd.VideoMax;\
\cf2 var\cf0  vm = \cf2 new\cf0  VideoMax();\
vm.setSize(640, 480);\
vm.setTint(0x1c1c1c, 0xffffff);\
vm.autoLoad = \cf2 true\cf0 ;   \cf4 // OR vm.setAutoLoad(true);\cf0 \
vm.autoPlay = \cf2 true\cf0 ;   \cf4 // OR vm.setAutoPlay(true);\cf0 \
vm.autoRewind = \cf2 true\cf0 ; \cf4 // OR vm.setAutoRewind(true);\cf0 \
vm.autoSize = \cf2 true\cf0 ;   \cf4 // OR vm.setAutoSize(true);\cf0 \
vm.buffer = 10;       \cf4 // OR vm.setBuffer(10);\cf0 \
vm.loop = \cf2 true\cf0 ;       \cf4 // OR vm.setLoop(true);\
\cf0 vm.playOverlay = \cf2 true\cf0 ;\
vm.showControls = \cf2 true\cf0 ;\
vm.showMiniStatus = \cf2 true\cf0 ;\
vm.showFirstFrame = \cf2 false\cf0 ;\
vm.showLastFrame = \cf2 false\cf0 ;\
vm.showEndFrames = \cf2 false\cf0 ;\
vm.source = \cf3 "sample.flv"\cf0 ;\
vm.\cf2 play\cf0 ();\
\cf2 addChild\cf0 (vm);
\f0 \
		\

\i ** NOTE: In Example 2, mp.play() needs to be called AFTER setting the attributes, even if the autoPlay attribute is set to true. This is because the autoPlay attribute's default value is set to 'false'. So when the VideoMax object is set, it will NOT play the video until instructed. Also, since you are setting attributes after creating the VideoMax instance, the attributes need to be recalculated, which happens when the 'play()' function is called. Lastly, if using Example 2, you do not have the ability to add 'onStart' and 'onComplete' commands, along with their accompanying parameters, unless you pass them as part of the attributes when creating the VideoMax instance.
